[suggestions]
  LENS     developer-experience
           The worldview focuses on what the tool does but not how it feels to use. A DX lens would explore: first-run experience, error message quality, configuration discovery, migration from markdownlint, time-to-value.
  LENS     adversarial-input
           Markdown is a loosely specified format with many dialects. An adversarial lens would explore pathological inputs: 100MB files, binary content with .md extension, circular symlinks, Unicode edge cases, markdown designed to confuse parsers.
  QUESTION Should this be a linter (report problems) or a formatter (fix problems) or both?
           The distinction between linting and formatting is blurry. Tools like prettier-markdown and mdformat chose formatting. markdownlint chose linting. The hybrid approach (lint + autofix) is harder but more valuable. This is a fundamental product decision.
  QUESTION What is the differentiation story against markdownlint?
           markdownlint is mature, widely adopted, and has VS Code integration. Building another markdown linter without a clear 'why this one' will struggle for adoption. Speed (Bun), zero-config, and superior autofix are candidate differentiators.
  SOURCE   https://spec.commonmark.org/
           The CommonMark spec is the baseline for what 'valid markdown' means. Many linter rules implicitly depend on parser behavior at spec edge cases. Understanding the spec prevents building rules that contradict it.
  SOURCE   https://github.com/DavidAnson/markdownlint/blob/main/doc/Rules.md
           markdownlint's rule catalog is the de facto standard for markdown lint rules. Studying it reveals which rules are most requested, most controversial, and most complex to implement.

